I question the use case of throwing an error on a widening cast. For a narrowing cast it makes sense, but not really here because all ints are valid longs. But we can do a workaround with an overload that accepts integers. When the compiler is looking for Delete, it can use the `long` version because an implicit cast exists. When we add a new Delete that takes ints this one becomes a closer match because the type is exact

    [HttpDelete]
    public IActionResult Delete([FromRoute]int requestId)
    {
        requestApiService.Delete(requestId);

        return NoContentResult();
    }

    //service
    public void Delete(long requestId, int platformClientId)
    {
        //some logic here
    }

    //service
    public void Delete(int requestId, int platformClientId)
    {
       throw new ArgumentException();
    }

If you write an overload that takes in an `integer`, you can mark it as `Obsolete`, which will generate a compiler warning. You can also add a custom `#warning` tag inside the method:

    [Obsolete(&quot;Please use the overload that takes a long&quot;)]
    public static void Delete(int requestId, int platformClientId)
    {
        #warning We don&#39;t like Int32 around here.

        // Call the correct method anyway?
        Delete((long) requestId, platformClientId);
    }

Now, when we call each of these methods, the first method (with the integer) gets underlined and the intellisense says, `&quot;&#39;Program.Delete(int, int)&#39; is obsolete: &#39;Please use the overload that takes a long&#39;&quot;`. Additionally, when we build the project, there will be two warnings:

    CS1030 #warning: &#39;We don&#39;t like Int32 around here.&#39;
    CS0612 &#39;Program.Delete(int, int)&#39; is obsolete: &#39;Please use the overload that takes a long&#39;

